<TEI.2><text><body><div1 type="alphabetic letter" n="D" org="uniform" sample="complete"><entryFree key="Dung-hill" type="main" opt="n"><orth extent="full" opt="n">Dung-hill,</orth> a heap of dung: <bibl n="shak. wiv 1.3.70" default="NO" valid="yes">Wiv. I, 3, 70</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. lll 5.1.81" default="NO" valid="yes">LLL V, 1, 81</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. lll 5.1.81" default="NO" valid="yes">LLL V, 1, 81</bibl> <bibl n="shak. ayl 1.1.16" default="NO" valid="yes">As I, 1, 16</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. h5 4.3.99" default="NO" valid="yes">H5 IV, 3, 99</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. 2h6 4.10.87" default="NO" valid="yes">H6B IV, 10, 87</bibl>. <bibl n="shak. lr 3.7.97" default="NO" valid="yes">Lr. III, 7, 97</bibl>. Used to denote a base extraction: <cit><quote>d. curs,</quote> <bibl n="shak. 2h4 5.3.108" default="NO" valid="yes">H4B V, 3, 108</bibl></cit>. <cit><quote>d. grooms,</quote> <bibl n="shak. 1h6 1.3.14" default="NO" valid="yes">H6A I, 3, 14</bibl></cit>. <bibl n="shak. 2h6 1.3.196" default="NO" valid="yes">H6B I, 3, 196</bibl>. A term of reproach for a person meanly born: <cit><quote>out, d.!</quote> <bibl n="shak. jn 4.3.87" default="NO" valid="yes">John IV, 3, 87</bibl></cit>. <bibl n="shak. lr 4.6.249" default="NO" valid="yes">Lr. IV, 6, 249</bibl>.
</entryFree></div1></body></text></TEI.2>